m_q.target_metric: Cluster assignments for countries based on socioeconomic and health factors
sub_questions: What are the relevant features to use for clustering (all numeric columns excluding country)?
What is the optimal number of clusters for this dataset?
Should the features be normalized/standardized before clustering?
Which clustering algorithm is most appropriate (K-means, hierarchical, DBSCAN)?
How should the features be represented in the output (original values or transformed values)?

schema_conflicts: data-dictionary.csv has 'Income' capitalized but Country-data.csv has 'income' lowercase

scale_issues: Features have vastly different scales (e.g., gdpp ranges to 50000+ while inflation is typically <30)
income and gdpp are in absolute currency values while exports, health, imports are percentages

format_notes: Country-data.csv has 167 rows of country data
country column is object type (string), all other columns are numeric
data-dictionary.csv provides metadata about the features

constraints: All numeric features (child_mort, exports, health, imports, income, inflation, life_expec, total_fer, gdpp) must be included in clustering
country column should be excluded from clustering features but retained for reference
Output must be saved as cluster.csv
Output must contain Feature_i columns (where i represents each feature dimension) and Cluster column
derived_filters: Remove or impute any rows with missing values in numeric columns before clustering
statistical_tests: Elbow method to determine optimal number of clusters
Silhouette score to validate cluster quality
output_format_requirements: Column names must be Feature_1, Feature_2, ..., Feature_9, Cluster (9 features total)
Feature columns should contain the feature values (likely standardized)
Cluster column should contain integer cluster labels
One row per country (167 rows expected)
